          content: "<h4>What is an Interval?</h4><p>An interval is simply the distance between two notes, measured in semitones (frets on guitar).</p><h4>The 12 Intervals You Need to Know:</h4><ol><li><strong>Unison (0 semitones)</strong> - Same note</li><li><strong>Minor 2nd (1 semitone)</strong> - One fret apart</li><li><strong>Major 2nd (2 semitones)</strong> - Two frets apart (whole step)</li><li><strong>Minor 3rd (3 semitones)</strong> - Three frets apart</li><li><strong>Major 3rd (4 semitones)</strong> - Four frets apart</li><li><strong>Perfect 4th (5 semitones)</strong> - Five frets apart</li><li><strong>Tritone/Aug 4th (6 semitones)</strong> - Six frets apart</li><li><strong>Perfect 5th (7 semitones)</strong> - Seven frets apart</li><li><strong>Minor 6th (8 semitones)</strong> - Eight frets apart</li><li><strong>Major 6th (9 semitones)</strong> - Nine frets apart</li><li><strong>Minor 7th (10 semitones)</strong> - Ten frets apart</li><li><strong>Major 7th (11 semitones)</strong> - Eleven frets apart</li><li><strong>Octave (12 semitones)</strong> - Twelve frets apart (same note, higher)</li></ol><h4>Why \"Perfect,\" \"Major,\" and \"Minor\"?</h4><ul><li><strong>Perfect</strong> intervals (unison, 4th, 5th, octave) sound very stable and consonant</li><li><strong>Major</strong> intervals sound bright and happy</li><li><strong>Minor</strong> intervals sound darker and more melancholic</li></ul>"
